	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Agricultural dimensions of the WTO trade policy review for Guinea Bissau, Togo and Côte d’Ivoire</h1>

			
			<h4>
												27 August 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The WTO review highlights the important role of agriculture in the economies of Guinea Bissau, Togo and Côte d’Ivoire. It highlights that since the 2008 food price crisis, the three governments – given their heavy reliance on imports of basic foodstuffs such as cereals – have taken steps to contain inflationary pressures by suspending import duties and VAT. The governments have also sought to support food production through ‘the provision of fertilisers, seeds and other inputs at subsidised prices’.</p><p>The review notes the success of Côte d’Ivoire in developing and diversifying its agricultural sector through the cultivation of coffee, rubber, fruit, cotton and oil palm, in addition to cocoa, of which it is the world's leading producer. Côte d’Ivoire is described as having ‘considerable potential for increasing the value added’ of agricultural exports, although ‘the agricultural processing industry declined sharply during the last decade’. In terms of agricultural policy, in November 2011 the government adopted a new plan to reform the agricultural sector, with implementation starting in the cocoa and coffee sectors at the beginning of 2012. An extensive range of export taxes is applied in the cocoa sector.</p><p>According to the WTO Secretariat, ‘in less than a decade, Guinea Bissau has made great strides in developing its food crop sector’, particularly recently under an FAO Special Programme for Food Security, which has increased efficiency and production. Nevertheless ‘a large deficit in cereals, notably rice’ still exists. Raw cashew nut exports mainly to India are the only agricultural export crop and are roughly equivalent in value to food imports. Under the April 2009 National Agricultural Investment Programme the government aims to be ‘self- sufficient in production of food crops by 2020’, although this will require a major expansion of government expenditure on agriculture.</p><p>In Guinea Bissau, ‘all agricultural products [tariffs] have been bound at the single rate of 40 per cent’. A substantial range of export taxes is charged on cashew nut exports.</p><p>Agriculture in Togo meanwhile ‘has enjoyed a remarkable boom since 2008’. According to the WTO, ‘this is to a large extent a reflection of the measures taken by the Government to improve food security, boost agricultural production, and attract private investment’. The government sets producer prices for export crops generally above those in neighbouring countries.</p><p>The government of Togo was the first West African state to sign a Comprehensive Africa Agriculture Development Programme (CAADP) compact, although government spending still falls far below the CAADP target.</p><p>Given its role as a transport services economy, ‘most of Togo's exports go to African countries, particularly Burkina Faso, Benin, Niger, Ghana and Nigeria.’</p><p>However, socio-political conflicts and the democratic deficit are held to have ‘considerably inhibited’ trade and economic development.</p><p>In terms of trade policy, a common CET exists within WAEMU, although rates exceeding the bound rate are applied in some instances. The WAEMU Commission continues its efforts to harmonise trade policies, although a highly varied range of additional taxes and levies continues to be applied. For example, the government of Côte d’Ivoire imposes a special import tax (TCI) aimed at cushioning ‘the impact of any sharp fall in world prices… and/or to offset unfair practices’. It also applies the degressive protection tax (TDP), which WAEMU has already abolished. The authorities in Guinea Bissau have also reportedly made use of ‘special import tax or the degressive protection tax’.</p><p>The WAEMU Commission also continues its efforts to promote the application of common standards, seeking to identify and eliminate ‘irregular practices such as abusive or illegal taxation and inspection formalities, attempts at tariff rearmament…, technical and administrative obstacles to community products and… extortion’.</p><p>In addition, goods re-exported within WAEMU attract a second collection of duty, undermining the free flow of goods within the customs territory. Problems also arise linked to efforts to harmonise WAEMU tariffs with the ECOWAS fifth tariff band of 35%.</p><p>According to the WTO, the exclusion of agricultural products from VAT and/or general sales tax ‘causes distortions in the trade in competing imported products and problems of national treatment’.</p><p>The WTO notes that ‘two of the three countries impose very high taxes on their agricultural exports’, giving rise to significant levels of smuggling (e.g. Togo, with little cocoa production, is now a growing cocoa exporter).</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>WTO, ‘Trade Policy Review: Côte d’Ivoire, Guinea Bissau and Togo’, 2–4 July 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp366_e.htm" target="_self">http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp366_e.htm</a></p><p>EU, ‘Stepping stone economic partnership agreement between Côte d'Ivoire, of the one part, and the European Community and its Member States, of the other part’, <i>Official Journal of the</i><i> </i><i>European Union</i>, L 59/3, 3 March 2009</p><p>
<a href="http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=OJ:L:2009:059:0003:0273:EN:PDF" target="_self">http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=OJ:L:2009:059:0003...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The WTO secretariat argues that the ongoing efforts of the WAEMU Commission to harmonise the application of trade policies are worthy of increased levels of ‘aid for trade’ support. This could potentially bring real benefits in terms of regularising trade flows in agricultural products, where smuggling is widespread.</p><p>Given current trade policy practices, a number of provisions included in signed interim EPAs could give rise to challenges. For example, in response to the high food prices prevailing since 2008, import duties were suspended for many products. However, this could potentially give rise to problems with any EPA ‘standstill clause’ provisions, which would serve to freeze in place exceptionally low import duties. Care will be needed in handling this issue if efforts to promote local food production are not to fall foul of the down cycles of increasingly volatile international markets.</p><p>In addition, potentially, prohibitions contained in the interim EPA concluded with Côte d’Ivoire on the abolition of export taxes (Article 16.1) could require substantial reforms in current taxation arrangements prior to the implementation of the EPA, if trade practice is not to be inconsistent with the commitments made under the EPA. This needs to be seen in the light of the qualifications contained in Sections 16.2 and 16.3, which may allow flexibility in this regard.</p>
		</div>
		
